Categories 1 and 2: Waters for which there is enough information to determine that water quality standards are attained for all or some of their designated uses.
Category 3: Waters for which there is not enough information to determine their status.
Category 4: Waters that are impaired, but have one of several different types of waterbody recovery plans.
Category 5: Waters that are impaired and do not yet have waterbody recovery plans. Also known as 303(d) list impaired waters.

Parameter: Qualitative or quantitative measurements of physical, chemical, or biological attributes such as temperatures, metals, or bacteria.
Designated Use: Water quality goals of a waterbody or portion thereof, in part, by designating the use or uses to be made of the water.
Attainment: Achieving attainment means that a waterbody is supporting all designated uses for the pollutant parameters evaluated. Impairement means that a waterbody is persistently exceeding criteria for one or more pollutants and not supporting all designated uses.
Acute/Chronic: Duration periods and frequency thresholds for toxic pollutants for their protection of aquatic life and human health vary depending on short term (acute) or longer-term (chronic) exposure.
Magnitude: Describes the allowable maximum or minimum numeric concentration of a pollutant determined to meet water quality standards and be protective of the designated use.
Frequency: Describes the allowable number of times a water quality criterion can be exceeded before water quality standards are not met and an impairment of the designated use occurs.
Duration: Describes the length of time a pollutant may be present and potentially impacting a designated use before the criterion is considered exceeded and water quality standards are not met.
